  "body": "## Simple Summary\r\nAdd an input to vyper which manually specifies the storage locations of variables.\r\n\r\n## Motivation\r\nWhen deploying upgrades to contracts, you may want to be able to ensure the layout of your new contract matches (or is a superset of) the old contract. This provides a mechanism to do so.\r\n\r\n## Specification\r\nAdd a flag (perhaps named `--storage-layout-file`) to the compiler which has the same format as the output of `vyper -f layout`, which overrides the locations of variables in storage. Example:\r\n```python\r\n# foo.vy\r\na: uint256\r\nb: uint256\r\n```\r\nwould normally generate the layout\r\n```json\r\n{\"foo\": {\"type\": \"uint256\", \"location\": \"storage\", \"slot\": 0}, \"bar\": {\"type\": \"uint256\", \"location\": \"storage\", \"slot\": 1}}\r\n```\r\nbut instead one could feed the following file to the compiler and it would swap the locations of the variables in storage:\r\n```json\r\n{\"foo\": {\"type\": \"uint256\", \"location\": \"storage\", \"slot\": 1}, \"bar\": {\"type\": \"uint256\", \"location\": \"storage\", \"slot\": 0}}\r\n```\r\n\r\n## Backwards Compatibility\r\nActually improves backwards compatibility because the compiler does not guarantee storage layout stability between versions; this allows a user to override a compiler change to the storage layout if needed.\r\n\r\n## Dependencies\r\nIf this VIP depends on any other VIPs being implemented, please mention them.\r\n\r\n## References\r\nAdd any references that this VIP might reference (other VIPs/issues, links to blog posts, etc.)\r\n\r\n## Copyright\r\nCopyright and related rights waived via [CC0](https://creativecommons.org/publicdomain/zero/1.0/)\r\n",
